                     <interp inst="t18320705-202-off1059" type="offenceSubcategory" value="pocketpicking"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18320705-202-cd1060" type="crimeDate">17th of June</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320705-202-off1059 t18320705-202-cd1060"></join>, 1 pocket-book, value 2d.; 2 skeins of thread, value 1d.; 2 half-crowns, 2 shillings, and 2 sixpences, the property of 
                     
                        <persName id="t18320705-202-victim1707" type="victimName">
                           Michael 
                           Stanley
                        <interp inst="t18320705-202-victim1707" type="surname" value="Stanley"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18320705-202-victim1707" type="given" value="Michael"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18320705-202-victim1707" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320705-202-off1059 t18320705-202-victim1707"></join>
                     </persName>
                     
                  , from his person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>MICHAEL STANLEY. I am a <rs id="t18320705-202-viclabel1061" type="occupation">navigator</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320705-202-victim1707 t18320705-202-viclabel1061"></join> - I have known the prisoner two months; he worked for the same master. On the 17th of June he and I went to a public-house about one o'clock; I had a pocket-book in my waistcoat pocket, containing two skeins of thread, two half-crowns, two shillings, and two sixpences - I fell asleep for near three quarters of an hour; when I awoke I missed the book and its contents - I inquired of the landlord about it: I saw the prisoner again at a quarter before three o'clock, up the street; I taxed him with taking my book - he denied it; I met an officer, who took him; I saw him searched, and one of the papers, which had been in my book, two skeins of thread, and a bit of blue ribbon were found on him, and the money stated.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320705-202-person1708">
                  WILLIAM 
                  BARROW
               <interp inst="t18320705-202-person1708" type="surname" value="BARROW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-202-person1708" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-202-person1708" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (Police-constable G 158). I took the prisoner, and found on him the money and these articles.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320705-202-person1709">
                  BENJAMIN 
                  WALKER
               <interp inst="t18320705-202-person1709" type="surname" value="WALKER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-202-person1709" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320705-202-person1709" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prosecutor and the prisoner came to my house, and had a pot of porter - the prosecutor pulled out a pocket-book, and gave me a shilling; in about three-quarters of an hour he said he had been robbed of his pocket-book; I said, "If you have been robbed, it is by your mate:" he went out to look for him, and brought him back.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. The prosecutor asked me to go and have some beer; I had 10s. in my pocket, and was going to buy some clothes.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18320705-202-verdict1062" type="verdictDescription">
